query.result:
1 Already the sun had reached the horizon 2 whose meridian circle covers 3 Jerusalem with its highest point;
4 and the night, which is opposite to it, encircles, 5 was coming out of Gange with the Scales, 6 which overcome the hours when it is noon;
7 so that the white and the red cheeks, 8 there where I was, of the beautiful Dawn 9 through too much age were becoming rancid.

43 From the stern stood the celestial steersman,
44 such that he would make [one] blessed even described;
45 and more than a hundred spirits were seated within.

49 Then he made the sign of the holy cross to them;
50 whereupon they all cast themselves onto the shore:
51 and the boat went, as it came, swiftly.

61 And Virgil responded: “You perhaps believe
62 that we are experienced in this place;
63 but we are pilgrims as you are.”

82 Of wonder, I believe, I painted myself;
83 for which the shadow smiled and withdrew,
84 and I, following her, pushed myself further.

85 Sweetly she said that I should rest;
86 then I knew who she was, and I prayed
87 that, to speak to me, she would stop a little.

